> ‘guard, ward’). The popularity of the personal name was largely due to its being the name of the sainted Anglo-Saxon king Edward the Confessor and of three kings in the 13th–14th centuries."]}]},{"name":"John","type":"FIRST","meanings":["Greek: the Lord gave graciously; whom Jehovah gave; whom Jehovah bestowed."],"variants":[]},{"name":"William","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Probably the most successful of all the Old French names of Germanic origin that were introduced to England by the Normans. It is derived from Germanic <i>wil</i> ‘will, desire’ + <i>helm</i> ‘helmet, protection’. The fact that it was borne by the Conqueror himself does not seem to have inhibited its favour with the ‘conquered’ population: in the first century after the Conquest it was the commonest male name of all, and not only among the Normans. In the later Middle Ages it was overtaken by   John  , but continued to run second to that name until the 20th century, when the picture became more fragmented."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"Lord John William Belward was born in 1013, in Normandy, France. He married Lady John William Belward about 1049, in Malpas, Cheshire, England. They were the parents of at least 1 son. He died in 1060, at the age of 47."},"et":{"1013–1060":"1013–1060","1013–Female":"1013–Surnud","1050–1134":"1050–1134","1013":"1013","1134":"1134","about 1049":"umbes 1049","1050":"1050","1060":"1060","Malpas, Cheshire, England":"Malpas, Cheshire, England","Normandy, France":"Normandie, Prantsusmaa"},"fi":{"1013–1060":"1013–1060","1013–Female":"1013–Kuollut","1050–1134":"1050–1134","1013":"1013","1134":"1134","about 1049":"noin 1049","1050":"1050","1060":"1060","Malpas, Cheshire, England":"Malpas, Cheshire, England","Normandy, France":"Normandie, Ranska"},"fr":{"1013–1060":"1013–1060","1013–Female":"1013–Décédée","1050–1134":"1050–1134","1013":"1013","1134":"1134","about 1049":"environ 1